TOTAL_PAGES: 1: Harmony Health Plan Selected to Participate in the Statewide Illinois Managed Care Medicaid Program
column7: CHICAGO and Tampa, Fla., Oct.19, 2017 /PRNewswire/ -- Harmony Health Plan, Inc. ("Harmony"), a subsidiary of WellCare Health Plans, Inc. (WCG), announced today it signed a contract with the Illinois Department of Healthcare and Family Services (HFS) to administer the state's new Medicaid managed care program statewide.  Under the new contract, the state's existing Family Health Plan/Affordable Care Act (FHP/ACA) and the Integrated Care and Managed Long-term Care programs will be combined into a single integrated care delivery system and will expand statewide.  The new program is expected to serve approximately 2.7 million beneficiaries in Illinois.

column7: With the latest Republican push to repeal and replace the Affordable Care Act on life support, MUFG Securities' Jason Twizell expects that the GOP will pivot to tax reform, looking to score a win.  Twizell writes that the lowering of the corporate tax rate would probably lead to a reduced effective tax rate, as well as a one-time earnings benefit on deferred taxes for those companies with a net deferred tax liability position.  For example, he estimates that a 20% corporate tax rate would add some 30% to his EPS estimates, and a 25% tax rate would add 20%.

TOTAL_PAGES: 1: Ex-WellCare general counsel pleads guilty in Florida Medicaid case
column7: An ex-general counsel of insurer  WellCare Health Plans Inc pleaded guilty on Wednesday in  federal court in Tampa to having made a false statement to  Florida's Medicaid program, prosecutors said, the latest former  executive to be convicted in the case.  Thaddeus Bereday, indicted along with four other former  WellCare executives in 2011, had been scheduled to face trial in  September after not going on trial in 2013 with the other  defendants for health reasons, prosecutors said.  Bereday's plea came after the U.S. Supreme Court in April  declined to hear an appeal by former WellCare Chief Executive  Todd Farha of his fraud conviction for his role in a scheme to  cheat the Medicaid health insurance program for the poor.

Bereday’s guilty plea closes one more chapter in a case that transformed WellCare (WCG), a health insurance company headquartered in Tampa that provides managed care for government-sponsored programs including Medicaid and Medicare.  The company, which paid more than $200 million in civil fines, penalties and restitution, has since established a “strong culture of compliance,” according to its CEO, Ken Burdick, and has continued to grow.

TOTAL_PAGES: 1: Kiran Patel’s health insurance firms agree to $32M settlement with the feds
column7: Several Tampa health care companies controlled by Dr. Kiran Patel, including managed care providers Freedom Health and Optimum Healthcare, agreed to pay $31.7 million to settle allegations that they violated federal law to boost reimbursements from Medicare.  In addition, Sidd Pagidipati, the former chief operating officer of Freedom Health, agreed to pay $750,000 to resolve his alleged role in one of the purported illegal schemes, which were violations of the False Claims Act, a press release from the U.S. Department of Justice said.  The settlement “sends a clear message to the managed care industry that the United States will hold managed care plan providers responsible when they fail to provide truthful information,” said Chad Readler, acting assistant attorney general in the Department of Justice’s civil division.

TOTAL_PAGES: 1: Former WellCare executives face deadline to repay $26M from fraud scheme
column7: Todd Farha, former CEO of WellCare Health Plans Inc., and Paul Behrens, former chief financial officer of the company, have a May 1 deadline to pay a combined $26 million in restitution and civil payments stemming from their convictions on health care fraud.  The payments by Farha and Behrens, who are both serving federal prison terms, will bring the case to a close, according to legal news site Lexology .  Farha must pay $12.5 million to the U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission and $7.5 million to WellCare, and Behrens will have to pay $4.5 million to the SEC and $1.5 million to WellCare, Lexology said.

TOTAL_PAGES: 1: U.S. high court won't review WellCare ex-CEO fraud conviction
column7: The U.S. Supreme Court on Monday  declined to hear an appeal by former WellCare Health Plans Inc  Chief Executive Todd Farha of his 2013 fraud conviction  for his role in a scheme to cheat the Medicaid health insurance  program for the poor.  Farha began serving a three-year sentence at a minimum  security federal prison in Alabama after the Atlanta-based 11th  U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals upheld his conviction in August  2016.  Farha had asked the justices to overturn his conviction,  taking issue with the trial judge's handling of his case.

TOTAL_PAGES: 1: U.S. raises Medicare payments to insurers by 0.45 pct in 2018
column7: [Reuters] - The U.S. government on Monday slightly improved its final payment rate for health insurers who offer Medicare Advantage plans for older people and the disabled, settling on an increase of 0.45 percent on average for 2018. Medicare Advantage, an alternative to the standard fee-for-service Medicare in which private insurers manage health benefits, is the fastest growing form of government healthcare, with enrollment of 18 million people last year. While the outlook for other forms of U.S. government healthcare uncertain under President Donald Trump, health insurers are banking on Republicans embracing the use of Medicare Advantage.

column7: [PR Newswire] - KAPOLEI, Hawaii and TAMPA, Fla., Feb. 8, 2017 /PRNewswire/ -- In Hawaii, more than 1 out of every 4 children ages 10 to 17 are considered overweight or obese, and the number of children engaged in four or more hours of screen time, including playing video games or watching television, each day is on the rise. To help promote active living and healthy eating in Hawaii schools, 'Ohana Health Plan, a WellCare Health Plans, Inc. (WCG) company, co-sponsored the Hawaii 5210 Let's Go! health promotion assembly on Jan. 31 at Pu'uhale Elementary School in Honolulu with Kaiser Permanente Community Benefit and Kokua Hawaii Foundation. The Hawaii 5210 team led an interactive health education assembly with students and staff, which promoted physical activity such as dance and the importance of drinking more water throughout the day.

(UAM) announced today that they have entered into a definitive agreement under which WellCare will acquire Universal American in an all cash transaction valued at $10.00 per share of common stock. This represents a 34 percent premium to Universal American's 60-day volume-weighted average closing stock price as of November 16, 2016.
